Fig.  3 (a) and (b) show true stress-strain curves of V x NbMoTa RHEAs at 800 • C and 1000 • C. Compared with the RT properties shown in Fig.  1  (a), the strength of all alloys decreases as increasing the temperature and the yield strength raises as the V concentration increases (Table  1 ), and there is no fracture (up to 50% strain) at high temperatures. As shown in Fig.  3(c) , at 800 • C, the V0.25 alloy shows the highest strain hardening rate, followed by the V0.5 alloy, and the V0.75 and V1.0 alloys exhibit similar strain hardening rates of the lowest values. Similarly, at 1000 • C (Fig.  3(d) ), the V1.0 alloy shows the lowest strain hardening rate while the other three alloys exhibit slightly higher strain hardening rates.
Mechanical properties and strengthening, deformation, and/or fracture mechanisms of novel VxNbMoTa RHEAs are investigated in this study.
